Question 1¶

Thyriod Dataset¶

The Thyroid Disease Dataset was made available online by Ross Quinlan in 1987. This Dataset consists of 6 databases and this particular dataset encompasses 3722 instances featuring 29 attributes pertinent to diagnosing thyroid ailments.

I chose this dataset because machine learning models can be highly benefitial in the healthcare industry. I wanted to try working with a dataset that I wasn't the most familiar with to challenge my understanding of the algorithms we've learnt and apply it on unfamiliar dataset.

Attributes¶

  1. Age: Age group intervals
  2. Sex: Gender groups
  3. On Thyroxine: On thyroxine status
  4. On anti-thyroid med: Anti-thyroid medication
  5. Query on thyroxine: if thyroxine is present in the body
  6. Sick: Current sick status
  7. Pregnant: Pregnant status
  8. Thyroid surgery: Had thyroid surgery
  9. I131: Had I131 treatment
  10. Query hypothyroid: Hypothyroidism statue
  11. Query hyperthyroid: Hyperthyroidism status
  12. Lithium: Lithium status
  13. Goiter: Goiter status
  14. Tumor: Tumor status
  15. Hypopituitary: Hypopituitary status
  16. Psych: Psych status
  17. TSH measured: if TSH was measured
  18. TSH: TSH level intervals (TSH=Normal (0.27≤ TSH ≤4.2); TSH=Abnormal (Not within the normal range))
  19. T3 measured: if T3 levels were measured
  20. T3: T3 level intervals (T3=Normal (1.3≤ T3 ≤ 3.1), T3=Abnormal (Not within the normal range))
  21. TT4 measured: if TT4 was measured
  22. TT4: TT4 level intervals (TT4=Normal (62≤ TT4 ≤ 164), TT4=Abnormal (Not within the normal range))
  23. T4U: if T4U was measured
  24. T4U: T4U level intervals (T4U=Normal (0.7≤ T4U ≤ 1.8), T4U=Abnormal (Not within the normal range))
  25. FTI measured: if FTI was measured
  26. FTI: FTI level intervals (FTI=Normal (53≤ FTI ≤142), FTI=Abnormal (Not within the normal range))
  27. TBG measured: if TBG was measured
  28. TBG: TBG levels
  29. binaryClass: Thyroid disease status (Negative (Does not have thyroid disease), Positive (Has thyroid disease))

Question 2¶

Research Question¶

How accurately can we predict thyroid disease diagnosis based on a patient's health data?

Human body works in complex ways. There are numerous anatominal processess that play a part in disease diagnosis. My aim is to use supervised learning to understand how we can accurately predict thyriod diagnosis based on patient's health data.

Question 3¶

I plan to use the decision tree algorithm to answer my research question, which is a regression problem. I am trying to predict which attributes provide the best diagnostic value. I believe decision tree is the optimal algorithm for this porblem because:

  1. A decision tree algorithm provides a natural way to measure feature importance in a dataset. It automatically selects the most informative attributes for splitting nodes in the tree, disregarding irrelevant or redundant features, which simplifies the model and improves generalization performance.
  2. Decision trees are highly interpretable. In a medical context it becomes very important to know and be able to explain to patients what aspects/factors lead to certain diseases, so they can make adequate lifestyle changes and treat the disease. For instance, if I were to use neural network to solve this problem, the hidden layers would obscure the decision making that went into the final outcome of the model. Therefore, a model like a decision tree helps us better interpret and answer the research question.

# Base Model

from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score
from sklearn.metrics import f1_score

# Defining independent and target variable
X = df_cleaned.drop(columns = ['binaryClass'])
y = df_cleaned['binaryClass']

#  Training and testing
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state= 15)

# Creating a Decision Tree classifier
dt_classifier = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=67, criterion="gini", max_depth=2)
dt_classifier.fit(X_train, y_train)

print(dt_classifier.feature_importances_)

# Predicting
y_pred_train = dt_classifier.predict(X_train)
y_pred = dt_classifier.predict(X_test)
print("Training Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_train, y_pred_train))

# Calculating accuracy, precision, and recall for Decision Tree Classifier
accuracy = round(accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred), 4)
print("Accuracy of Model 1(Decision Tree):", accuracy)
precision = round(precision_score(y_test, y_pred), 4)
print("Precision of Model 1(Decision Tree):", precision)
recall = round(recall_score(y_test, y_pred), 4)
print("Recall of Model 1(Decision Tree):", recall)
f1 = f1_score(y_test,y_pred)
print("F1 score of Model 1(Decision Tree):",f1)

Subsequently, 'T3 measured', 'TT4 measured', 'T4U measured', 'FTI measured', 'TSH measured' all have information that have already been captured in our dataset, so I am dropping those too.

Analysis: With a dataset split 20-80 (test-train), and criteria being gini, and max depth of 2, I get model accuracy of 99.2% and F1 score of 99.5 %, which is very high. Question 6¶

Changing the dataset structure to use categorical data instead of numerical data

Base Model. Parameters (Max Depth: 2, Criterion: gini, Data Type: Numerical). Results (Accuracy: 0.9924, Recall: 0.9756, F1 score: 0.9523)

Categorical Model. Parameters (Max Depth: 2, Criterion: gini, Data Type: Categorical). Results (Accuracy: 0.9206, Recall: 0.0244, F1 score: 0.0455)

For the first analysis, we further processed the raw data set by using literature values for the numerical values as explained above. We see a significant decrease in both accuracy, recall and F1 score by doing so. This is what we would expect because by further processing and turning numerical values in booleans, we are removing information from the core dataset. In the base model, the decision tree model can decide what decision boundary values it wants to use for T3 for example and decide to split on T3 between 2 and 3. However by converting to boolean, we forced the decision of the boundary to between 1.3 and 3.1 and converted the values to True/False. With the categorical dataset, the model can only split the decision between True and False now which is a set interval of (1.3, 3.1). This further shows that even though we used literature values to convert the numerical values to "normal" and "abnormal" denominations, machine learning models are made significantly better when given more information as it can form its own inferences and patterns to reach an optimal solution.

Changing the criterion for the decision tree

Base Model. Parameters (Max Depth: 2, Criterion: gini, Data Type: Numerical). Results (Accuracy: 0.9924, Recall: 0.9756, F1 score: 0.9523)

Entropy Model. Parameters (Max Depth: 2, Criterion: entropy, Data Type: Numerical). Results (Accuracy: 0.9924, Recall: 0.9756, F1 score: 0.9524)

Log Loss Model. Parameters (Max Depth: 2, Criterion: log_loss, Data Type: Numerical). Results (Accuracy: 0.9924, Recall: 0.9756, F1 score: 0.9524)

Keeping all other factors the same, I tinkered with the criterion for the decision tree between "gini", "entropy" and "log_loss". The criterion formula is used by the model to decide the "quality" of the split and decide what attribute and where to split. The gini impurity defines optimal splits to minimize the probability of a particular variable being wrongly classified when it is randomly chosen. The log loss criterion compares output of different splits to the actual class labels and penalizes incorrect classifications to minimize the "information loss". Entropy maximizes information gain by quantifying the entropy in the dataset before and after the split and minimizing the amount of uncertainty. Often, the different criterion lead to different results when there are two fairly equally "good" splits that could occur but the different criterions chose one over the other based on what they are prioritizing. We would expect model performance to differ with the 3 criterion but in our case, all 3 models were identical. This points to the data characteristic and complexity being simple, such that all 3 criterion aligned on the same optimal splits even with different underlying mathematical formulations. This means that any of the criterion led to optimal splits and any can be used for this specific dataset and problem.

Question 8¶

Problems

  1. I think the main problem is that my dataset is highly skewed. With only 216 rows of data where a patient has been diagnosed with thyroid and a substantially more number of rows 2427 where the patient has not been diagnosed. This skewed dataset has led to a biased model performance, wherein the decison tree algorithm has been trained mostly on patient data who haven't been diagnosed, resulting in poor predictive performance for the minority class, that is patients who have been diagnosed with thyriod.
  2. Working with this biased dataset has meant that I cannot rely on accuracy to evaluate my model because accuracy in cases of imbalenced dataset. I can only evaluate my model using either precision, recall, or F1 scores.
  3. Accuracy of the model was already high with very few attributes because of the simplistic nature of the dataset. This made it hard to evaluate model performance when changing model parameters.

Although real-world data is often imperfect, the way to overcome these challenges is to have a more balanced dataset to begin with to ensure that our training and testing is happening on a balanced dataset that further ensures a more accurate predictive analysis. We can achieve this by oversampling the minority class to ensure that we have a balanced dataset.

Question 9¶

Explain how your machine learning solution answers the research question you defined.

The research question I set out to answer was: How accurately can we predict thyroid disease diagnosis based on a patient's health data? My model answers the question by providing evaluation parameters such as accuracy, recall, precision, and F1 score. As explained in the previous question, accuracy is not the most accurate measure of model performance. Therefore, I rely on recall to answer this question. The recall rate is 0.9756, which indicates that the model has been able to perform well. We can conclude that we have been able to answer the research question. However, as I will go on to analyze this further, the overall performace of my model comes in question given how skewed my dataset is.

In its current state, there are more risks than advantages in deploying this model to unseen data. Firstly, the small sample size means that our model has not seen enough data, making it hard to make generalized predictions on most population sizes. It will likely yield low accuracy if we test it on data that is more varied, especially for the positive cases. Second, it predicts thyroid disease based on very specific attributes, which limits the usability in real life. For instance, we cannot use a different types of test to predict thyroid. It has to be these specific attributes that need to be deployed to make any sort of prediction.

The consequences of my solution being wrong are the high number of false positives and false negatives that arise out of this model. In the case of false positives, where the model has falsely diagnosed patients as having thyroid. This can lead to elevated stress for the patient as well burden the healthcare system with treating them with more tests before the right diagnosis can be achieved. In the case of false negatives, my model can have graver consequences. Patients who have the disease and haven't been correctly diagnosed can have their symptoms worsen.

There are of course advantages when the model is right. This model provides great early predictive power on the basis of preliminary attributes, which tent to be less invasive tests, till further more invasive procedures can be deployed to concretely diagnose a thyroid patient.

Positive impacts of my model are the lessened burden on healthcare system to diagonse thyroid disease. On the basis of a few attributes, the hospital will be able to ascertain which person is more or less suseptible to being diagnosed with the disease. This will save millions of dollars in further diagnostic costs for the patients as well as help detect the disease early on. Negative impacts of my model are the lack of generalizability, which would have been highly advantageous to help predict the prevelance of thyroid in different populations around the world.

Question 10¶

Another research question: "What are the key risk factors associated with thyroid disease development, and how do they interact with each other?"

Understanding the key risk factors for thyroid disease is quite important. If we are able to correctly predict which factors are most closely associated with the disease, we can help patients better by improving prevention and early detection. We can also provide better personalized treatment as we'd be able to understand what factors increase risks of the disease and provide insights to patients to better manage their disease.
